ia9JwpxIwHvcDZAIXA-4GkaP53eZOL0hGGaMTIcitbt7g2Q==\\\",\\\"summary\\\":[{\\\"type\\\":\\\"summary_text\\\",\\\"text\\\":\\\"**Evaluating server implementation**\\\\n\\\\nI'm thinking about how Forge generates metadata externally from the test run, which is good since we don’t have to edit it ourselves. However, I wonder if adding a dependency could complicate things? Using a public API might be necessary, but it seems like incorporating akka-stream is crucial for this API. On another note, if I use `java.net.ServerSocket`, I have to be cautious about blocking behavior during connection acceptance and how to handle exceptions properly.\\\"}]}\"}, {\"type\": \"text\", \"text\": \"Fixed the compilation issue by adding Akka Stream to the test project dependencies:\\n\\n- Updated `tests/src/com.typesafe.akka/akka-http-core_3/10.6.0-M1/build.gradle`\\n\\nAdded:\\n\\n```gradle\\ntestImplementation 'com.typesafe.akka:akka-stream_3:2.9.0-M2'\\n```\\n\\n`akka-http-core_3` declares `akka-stream_3` as a `provided` dependency, so it was not available on the test compile classpath. The new `Http2AlpnSupportTest` uses public Akka HTTP/Stream APIs, so the test project needs that dependency explicitly.\", \"textSignature\": \"{\\\"v\\\":1,\\\"id\\\":\\\"msg_04a73ab565b108c60169fc6de04924819f91ce1ee1eba844b6\\\",\\\"phase\\\":\\\"final_answer\\\"}\"}], \"api\": \"openai-responses\", \"provider\": \"OCA\", \"model\": \"gpt-5.5\", \"usage\": {\"input\": 733, \"output\": 655, \"cacheRead\": 36352, \"cacheWrite\": 0, \"totalTokens\": 37740, \"cost\": {\"input\": 0, \"output\": 0, \"cacheRead\": 0, \"cacheWrite\": 0, \"total\": 0}}, \"stopReason\": \"stop\", \"timestamp\": 1778150869583, \"responseId\": \"resp_04a73ab565b108c60169fc6dd6329c819fb4761ada426d56dc\"}, \"toolResults\": []}\n../5005-ebf0f0b1/human-intervention-logs/com.typesafe.akka:akka-http-core_3:10.6.0-M1/metadata-fix/codex.log:7:{\"type\":\"item.completed\",\"item\":{\"id\":\"item_2\",\"type\":\"command_execution\",\"comman